Peel the @Kiwi{1}, halve lengthways and then chop into 1cm chunks. Halve the @Red Chilli{1} lengthways, deseed then finely chop. Trim the @Spring Onion{1} and thinly slice. Zest and halve the @Lime{1}. Pop the kiwi, chilli and spring onion into a #bowl{} and squeeze in the lime juice and @Olive Oil{1%tbsp}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, mix together then set aside.

Pour the @Water{300%ml} for the rice into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, add @salt{0.25%tsp}, stir in the @Jasmine Rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Halve the @Sugar Snap Peas{80%g} lengthways down the middle, peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Once hot, add the sugar snap peas and stir fry until tender, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}, then pop the sugar snaps in a bowl and cover with #foil{} to keep warm.

Return the frying pan to a medium high heat and add a drizzle of oil. Season the @Salmon Fillets{2} with salt and pepper, then lay it in the pan skin side down. Fry for ~{4-5%minutes}, then turn and cook for ~{4-5%minutes} on the other side. Once cooked, carefully peel the skin off the salmon and discard.

> The salmon is cooked when it is opaque in the middle

Remove the pan from the heat and use a #fork{} to pull apart the salmon into large flakes. Add the @Teriyaki Sauce{50%ml} to the pan and gently toss to combine and coat the salmon in the sauce.

Fluff up the rice with a fork and stir through the lime zest. Serve the rice in #bowls{} with the salmon on top in one third, then kiwi salsa (including the juices) in another third and the garlicky sugar snaps on the other third. Enjoy!